<font color="#FF0000">MY COUNTRY, MY LAND</font><br>
<tt>Tue Aug 26 21:48:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
From the top of hill 65 you could see for miles. The air was clean, sweet smelling and wet.  You could smell and taste the moistness of the grounds red dirt in the air. The countryside that surrounded the hill was filled with bright green rice paddies. South of the hill a large village was located on the other side of the road we had traveled on, Route 4. Eastward on Route 4 was the sea coast and the city of Hoi An.  Route 1 led from there North into DaNang or South toward Saigon.  On the other side of the road the murky brown waters of the Song Vu Gia River flowed leisurely eastbound. A short distance away the river splits going north where it feeds into the Song Cau Do River and south where the river takes on a snake like appearance, then mingles with the rapid waters of the Song Thu Bon River. <br>
The small dirt roadway at the bottom of the hill ran westward through the villages and further away one could see a small bridge. The villages, the road, the river, the bridge, the emerald colored paddies all added a mystical feeling as well as beauty to the overall landscape. <br><br>
Sorry guys, just reminiscing for B who lost his country.<br><br>
Drop by our India Company web site put together by a fellow Marine that was there in 1967-1967.<br><br>
http://washington.xtn.net/~grunt/vietnam/<br>

